description:
Adult San Diego Gophersnake (Pituophis catenifer annectens) discovered active at mid-day among farm equipment and debris adjacent to an agricultural field, western San Diego County, California

In an attempt to intimidate me it coiled into a strike position, flattened its head and neck, gaped its mouth, lolled its tongue, and hissed loudly. It reverted to a total pussycat as soon as I picked it up. It also tried to make a getaway in my backpack.

According to GoogleEarth, this place was turned into a high-density housing development in 2010.

description:
I was sitting on a bench next to a trail enjoying the view when I noticed a coyote on the slope below me who was making his way uphill, eyeing me while he circled around. When he finally reached my level he trotted away down the trail until he disappeared around the bend. A second later a big dumb dog came loping along in the opposite direction  acting oblivious to the coyote that he had just missed. A minute or so later his people finally showed up. 

I wish I could have seen that. They were in the same spot nearly at the same time.  How did the coyote hide from the dog?  The dog didn't act like he had just seen or smelled anything unusual.  I guess the dog was super good-natured and didn't care.

description:
Here are some other exmaples of milliped we found while looking for Hydromantes shastae. 

This millipede form was totally new to me, I had never seen any like this before. In the Merced river area we found more or less the same looking ones but with a much nicer pink color...

Contrary to centipedes (which are meat eaters) the millipedes eat plant debri. They have 4 legs per segment whereas centipedes only 2.

description: Came across a boy on the trail holding a newt so naturally I took pics. This photo was used in this article in Scientific American about changing habitats and 'assisted migration'. www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=california-amph...
On the trail to sentinel rock. (Jepson)
These flowers were so tiny I can't believe I managed to get a shot looking up at them. Growing on the hillside behind the West Coast Memorial to the Missing of World War II in the Presidio. (Jepson)

I went back to Windy Hill yet again to shoot this batch growing on the dead log by the park entrance. Most were closed but a few were still open. Afterwards I hiked up the Meadow Trail and found the mother lode of miner's lettuce under a big gnarly oak. It was pretty spectacular. Photo taken by Dawn Endico at the Alpine Road park entrance at Windy Hill Open Space Preserve, March 23, 2006. (Jepson)
Growing in grassland at the intersection of Spring Ridge Trail and Meadow trail. It was a small plant with just one blossom and was the only one of its kind I saw. (Geotagged) (Jepson)
Mitchell Canyon Trail at Mount Diablo, California
I found it growing on a hillside along the Betsy Crowder Trail in shaded woods and wet soil. (Jepson)

On Hamms Gulch Trail where the trail crosses the creek, next to Alpine Road.

This trail was loaded with wildflowers today. Red trillium, buttercups, milk maids, plus teensy vetch, forgetmenots, miner's lettuce, and chickweed whose blossoms were only about the size of my little fingernail.

I found it growing on a hillside along the Betsy Crowder Trail in shaded woods and wet soil. They look a lot different in this shot where their blossoms are open and facing up. Photo taken by Dawn Endico on the Betsy Crowder Trail at Windy Hill Open Space Preserve, March 11, 2006. (Jepson)

description:
A red beetle with comb like antennae. According to the R. T. Peterson guide this insect is in one of the beetle families due to more than 5 segments on the antennae. 

The size of my thumb is 15/16 of and inch. When I zoomed out of the image on my computer to fit my thumb, this gave a measurement of 7/16 of and inch to the insect. 

The location of where i saw this insect is not exact but approximate to where I remembered being and within a 2 mile radius. 

The tree the insect was seen on is a California Wild Lilac tree (Ceanothus thyrsiflorus).

I am continuing to investigate the species name but hopefully someone who is an expert and can utilize the information given to give me a solid scientific name for this animal. 

Email me for additional questions. Paul
